Title : Arto Antturi
Text : {{Orphan|date=April 2016}}

'''Arto Kai Antturi'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helsinginhiippakunta.evl.fi/hallinto_ja_lakiasiat/vaalit/kirkolliskokous-ja_hiippakuntav/hiippakuntavaltuuston-pappisjase2/|title=Hiippakuntavaltuuston pappisjäsenten vaalin tulos - Helsingin hiippakunnan tuomiokapituli|website=www.helsinginhiippakunta.evl.fi}}</ref> (born [[Helsinki]], 10 June 1961)<ref name="KATH">[http://www.katharos.fi/index.php?page=kirjailijat Katharos - Kirjailijat<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504135740/http://www.katharos.fi/index.php?page=kirjailijat |date=May 4, 2014 }}</ref> is a [[Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland|Finnish Lutheran]] priest. He is the vicar for the parish of [[Pitäjänmäki]].

[[File:Arto Antturi bassolla.jpg|thumb|Pastor Arto Antturi (right) on the bass in the Old Church of Helsinki, where he was chaplain.]]
Arto Antturi’s father was the [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] minister Kai Antturi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sana.fi/ihmiset/haastattelut/arto_antturi_toisten_vahattely_vie_voimia_kirkolta_/|title=Sinulle - Kansan Raamattuseura|website=www.sana.fi}}</ref> Arto Antturi graduated with a [[Master's degree|master’s]] degree in [[theology]] from the [[University of Helsinki]] in 1989. For most of the 1990s, he worked as a research and teaching assistant in the Department of [[Exegesis]] at the same university. He received a scholarship from the [[Alfred Kordelin]] Foundation in 1992. In 1997, he received a grant from the [[Finnish Cultural Foundation]]. He has studied at [[Vanderbilt University]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], USA.

Later, Antturi lived with his family in [[Dublin]] for two years, serving as a priest for the [[Finnish Seamen’s Mission]].<ref name="KATH" /> At the beginning of 2000, he was appointed as the Executive Director of the Helsinki-based Thomas Community. In 2003, he became a priest in the Cathedral parish and in 2010 became a chaplain in that parish. He served as chaplain at the [[Helsinki Old Church]] from 2010 to 2014. He took his office as vicar of [[Pitäjänmäki]] on 1 January 2015.

Antturi has been involved in various media work and public duties. In 1987, Antturi co-founded the gospel band Exit and played bass in the band from 1987 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exityhtye.com/biografia/|title=Biografia – Exit|website=www.exityhtye.com}}</ref> He was a deputy councillor in Helsinki City Council for the [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]] in 1997.<ref>https://www.webcitation.org/6MOsEkwIG?url=http://fi.linkedin.com/in/artoantturi [https://www.webcitation.org/6MOsG4zKw?url=http://www.hel.fi/static/helsinki/vuosikertomukset/Hki_vuosikertomus_1997_fi/suomi/kvaltuusto97.html the Helsinki city council in 1997]</ref> He has served as the editor of the Thomas Community from 2000 to 2003, as well as a columnist for other magazines, including that for Radio Dei. He has broadcast devotions on [[Yle]] Radio 1.<ref name="KATH" /> In 2009, Antturi ran a fundraising campaign at the Narinkka Square in Helsinki called “The Priest and The Idiot”, in which he read [[Fyodor Dostoyevsky|Dostoevsky's]] work ''[[The Idiot]]''  for 10 euros a page. This was to raise funds for [[World Vision|World Vision’s]] work with poor families in [[Kenya]].<ref>[http://www.worldvision.fi/media/artikkelit/artikkeli/pappi-ja-idiootti-tekivat-sivukaupalla-hyvaa-helsingin-kampissa Pappi ja Idiootti tekivät sivukaupalla hyvää Helsingin Kampissa | Artikkelit | Media | World Vision<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

